<target_code>
Here is the code of UtList_Destroy:

```c
void UtList_Destroy(UtListHead_t *ListHead)
{
    uint32 i;

    for (i = 0; i < ListHead->NumberOfTags; ++i)
    {
        UtList_Reset(&ListHead->Tags[i]);
    }
    free(ListHead);
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are related to the target function UtList_Destroy:
void UtList_Reset(UtListNode_t *TagHead)
{
    while (!UtList_IsEmpty(TagHead))
    {
        UtList_DeleteNode(TagHead->Next);
    }
}
...
void UtList_DeleteNode(UtListNode_t *DeleteNode)
{
    UtList_Extract(DeleteNode);

    /* non-data/header nodes shouldn't be free()'ed */
    if (DeleteNode->Data != NULL)
    {
        free(DeleteNode);
    }
}
</additional code>
Please find suspicious code fragments in the code and report them. Other agents can not investigate other fragments that you do not report, so it is very important to find all suspicious fragments without missing any. Report the suspicious fragments AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.
explanation: I inspected the provided code (UtList_Destroy, UtList_Reset, UtList_DeleteNode and the shown calls). There are no uses of memcmp (nor strcmp/strncmp) or any string comparison on null-terminated strings in the presented fragments. The functions operate on list nodes, pointers and call free(), but do not perform byte-wise comparisons of C strings. Therefore there are no code fragments in the supplied code that violate MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.14. (If additional functions such as UtList_Extract or other modules exist, those should be searched for any memcmp usages — none appear in the shown code.)
